-- Liliana Study 3 dry-run: attach real consent form, debrief form, and
-- screener content — three gaps found in the 2026-07-14 audit (studies with
-- no active_consent_form_id/active_debrief_form_id fall back to generic
-- off-topic RADlab boilerplate; no screener was ever attached to any
-- Liliana study record despite the emotion-regulation-v1 screener existing
-- in the screeners table since 2026-06-23 and the methods doc documenting
-- "Screener -> consent -> Baseline" for Day 1).
--
-- Content sourced from I:\Shared drives\Liliana\Study3\Ethics\ (Informed
-- Consent Form_LW.docx, Debriefing Form_LW.docx — converted to HTML via
-- mammoth, the same library the admin upload flow uses) and
-- Questionnaires_logic\screener-emotion-regulation-v1.json /
-- screener-preview.html (the "description" block below reproduces the
-- preview's Screen A copy, which the existing screeners.definition row
-- never had — ScreenerPage.jsx falls back to a generic one-liner without it).

-- 1. Screener: add the missing description block to the existing reusable
--    screener definition, then attach it to the dry-run study (mirrors
--    StudyDetail.jsx's "attach screener" action: copies definition into
--    both studies.screener_id and studies.screener).
UPDATE screeners
SET definition = definition || jsonb_build_object('description', $desc${
  "part_label": "Part A — Description of Study Design",
  "intro": [
    "Thank you for considering participation in our study. The purpose of this study is to examine the impact of brief (~4 min), daily online interventions on emotional well-being.",
    "In this fully online study, you will be asked to:"
  ],
  "steps": [
    "Complete a pre-screening form to determine eligibility.",
    "If eligible, complete an online consent form and a baseline assessment of your wellbeing and demographics <em>(~30 minutes)</em>.",
    "For 12 days, complete brief daily online interventions and report on your mood, stress, engagement, and enjoyment <em>(~4 min per day)</em>.",
    "Complete a midpoint assessment of your wellbeing and intervention preference <em>(~20 minutes)</em>.",
    "For an additional 12 days, complete daily online interventions and report on your mood, stress, engagement, and enjoyment <em>(~4 min per day)</em>.",
    "Complete a final assessment and receive a debriefing form about the study <em>(~25 minutes)</em>."
  ],
  "info_boxes": [
    "<strong>Minimum participation requirement:</strong> To continue participating in each phase of the study, you must complete a minimum of <strong>10 out of 12</strong> daily intervention and check-in sessions within that phase. If you complete fewer than 10 sessions in a given phase, your participation in that phase will be discontinued. You will still receive compensation for the portion of the study you completed.",
    "If you experience any discomfort at any point, please feel free to email the experimenter with your concerns. If your study participation is terminated — whether you choose to leave or stop participating in daily sessions — you will receive compensation for the portion completed up to the date of withdrawal.<br><br>You may request that your data be removed from the study up until your data are de-identified <strong>(anticipated November 1, 2026)</strong>. After this date, identifying information will have been permanently removed, and it will no longer be possible to withdraw your data."
  ]
}$desc$::jsonb)
WHERE slug = 'emotion-regulation-v1';

UPDATE studies s
SET screener_id = sc.id,
    screener    = sc.definition
FROM screeners sc
WHERE s.id = 'dddddddd-0000-4000-8000-000000000001'
  AND sc.slug = 'emotion-regulation-v1';

-- 2. Consent form
WITH ins AS (
  INSERT INTO study_consent_forms (study_id, html_content)
  VALUES ('dddddddd-0000-4000-8000-000000000001', $consent$<p><strong>Informed Consent Form</strong></p><p>I agree to participate in a study to examine the impact of brief online interventions on my emotional well-being. I understand that my participation is entirely voluntary: I can leave the study at any time, and this will have no bearing on the compensation I have already earned, nor will it have any other undesirable consequences.</p><p>The following points have been explained to me:</p><ol><li>The purpose of this research is to examine whether brief daily online interventions may improve perceived stress. I understand that I will be asked to answer some longer surveys at the start, middle, and end of the study, and to do brief online interventions and reflections (~4 min) each day during the study.</li><li> I understand that I may be assigned to one of three different online interventions, and that all interventions are designed to focus on emotional well-being. </li><li>Procedure. In this fully online study, you will be contacted by email over 31 days, and asked to:</li><li>Complete this consent form, baseline assessment of your wellbeing, intervention preference, and demographics questionnaire (~ 30 minutes).</li><li>For 12 days complete brief online daily interventions and report on your mood, stress, engagement, and enjoyment (~ 4 min per day). </li><li>Complete a midpoint assessment again measuring your wellbeing and report your intervention preferences (~ 20 minutes). </li><li>For an additional 12 days complete brief online daily interventions and report on your mood, stress, engagement, and enjoyment (~ 4 min per day).</li><li>Complete a final wellbeing assessment and receive a debriefing form about the study (~ 25 minutes)</li><li>Compensation. If you complete all study elements you will receive 3 hours of course credit. Each daily intervention and check-in link will be provided to you in an email sent each morning. Each of the 3 major assessments (baseline, midpoint, and final) contributes approximately 30, 20, and 25 minutes of credit respectively, for a combined total of ~1.25 hours.  The remaining ~1.75 hours come from completing the daily interventions and check-ins (24 sessions × ~4 minutes each). To receive full credit for each phase, you are expected to complete at least 10 out of 12 daily sessions within that phase. If you complete fewer than 10 sessions in a phase, you will receive credit only for the sessions completed in that phase, rounded up to the nearest half hour. If you withdraw early, you will receive credit for the portions of the study you completed, rounded up to the nearest half hour.</li><li>Benefits. The benefits I may expect to receive from this study are: (a) exposure to brief techniques related to adaptive emotion regulation (b) an appreciation of research on emotion and wellbeing, (c) an opportunity to contribute to scientific research, and (d) up to 3 hours of course credit compensation in PSY100, PSY201, or PSY202.</li><li>Risks. The study is considered minimal risk. The activities in this study involve completing questionnaires about mood and participating in brief online well-being exercises. Although these exercises are designed to promote well-being and positive coping strategies, the researchers acknowledge that some participants may experience temporary emotional discomfort when reflecting on their thoughts or feelings. This study is intended for students experiencing moderate symptoms of stress and low mood. <em>It is not a clinical treatment.</em> If you experience feelings of discomfort at any point during the study, you may refrain from answering any question or withdraw from the study at any time before your data are deidentified (anticipated November 1<sup>st</sup> , 2026) without penalty. You will receive compensation for the portion of the study you have completed up to the time of withdrawal. Information about appropriate campus and community mental health resources with provided throughout the study, including at each daily-check in. </li><li>Withdrawal / Leaving the Study. Your participation in this study is voluntary. You may withdraw from the study at any time without negative consequences. You may miss up to 2 of the 12 daily intervention sessions/check-ins in each study phase and remain enrolled. If you miss more than 2 intervention sessions/check-ins during either Phase 1 or Phase 2, you may be discontinued from the study. If this happens, you will still receive compensation for the portion of the study you completed. You may request that your data be removed from the study <strong>up until your data are deidentified (anticipated on </strong>November 1<sup>st</sup> , 2026) After this date, your identifying information (such as name and email) will be permanently removed and replaced with a SONA ID. Once this process is complete, the research team will no longer be able to link your identity to your data. Because your data will no longer be identifiable after November 1<sup>st</sup> , 2026. it will not be possible to withdraw your data beyond this point. If you choose to withdraw before deidentification, you will receive compensation for the portion of the study you have completed. If you do feel any discomfort at any point, please feel free to raise those concerns to the experimenter. If necessary, participation may be discontinued to protect your well-being. </li><li>Confidentiality. All data collected will remain strictly confidential, and I will be referred to only through my SONA ID. Only people associated with the study will see my responses. My name will never be recorded. However, to receive daily intervention and check-in links, I will be asked to provide my email address, which is identifying information. Once the study is complete, or no later than November 1<sup>st</sup>, 2026, all identifying information will be removed from the study. After this point, my data will be fully deidentified, and it will no longer be possible to determine which data belong to me, even if requested.</li><li>Data Storage. Once the study is complete and all the data has been de-identified, we will share the dataset indefinitely on the Open Science Framework (osf.io), which other researchers can access. We do not believe there is any chance that someone will be able to discover your identity using this data. Once data is posted to the Open Science Framework, we will no longer be able to remove your data if you decide you wish to withdraw consent. </li><li>Contact. The researcher will answer any other questions about the research either now or during the course of the experiment.  If I have any other questions or concerns, I can address them to the researcher or to principal investigator:  Prof. Norman Farb, <a href="mailto:norman.farb@utoronto.ca">norman.farb@utoronto.ca</a> or by phone at 905-828-3959. If you have concerns about the treatment of research participants, please contact the University of Toronto Ethics Review Office by phone at 416-946-3273, or by email at <a href="mailto:ethics.review@utoronto.ca">ethics.review@utoronto.ca</a>.</li><li>Upon completion of my participation, I will receive a full written explanation about the rationale and predictions underlying this experiment.  I may also receive a copy of this consent form by saving this page or by emailing a request for the form to the experimenter above.</li></ol><p>Agreement:</p><p>By signing below, I show that I have fully read and understood the process of this study. I understand that:</p><ul><li>I may be randomized to one of three different interventions focused on adaptive emotion regulation skills.</li><li>I am expected to fill out the three major wellbeing assessments at the start, midpoint, and end of the study.</li><li>I am expected to respond to and complete complete at least 10 out of 12 daily sessions within <strong><em>each </em></strong>12-day intervention period.</li><li>I understand that this study is intended for individuals who may be experiencing moderate symptoms of stress and low mood. and who do not have any known reasons that would prevent them from safely participating in daily online interventions and reflections on mood and stress.</li><li>I also understand that my participation in this study is completely voluntary and I may withdraw my participation at any time before my data is deidentified (anticipated on November 1st, 2026) without any negative consequences.</li></ul>$consent$)
  RETURNING id
)
UPDATE studies
SET active_consent_form_id = ins.id,
    consent_required = true
FROM ins
WHERE studies.id = 'dddddddd-0000-4000-8000-000000000001';

-- 3. Debrief form
WITH ins AS (
  INSERT INTO study_debrief_forms (study_id, html_content)
  VALUES ('dddddddd-0000-4000-8000-000000000001', $debrief$<p><strong>Debriefing Form</strong></p><p>Thank you for your participation in our study.</p><p>In daily life, we are constantly faced with stressors that demand our time, energy, and attention. While many challenges are unavoidable, the way we interpret and respond to them can make a meaningful difference in our emotional well-being. Importantly, some ways of thinking can increase stress (e.g., repeatedly dwelling on negative thoughts or being overly self-critical). These patterns are linked to anxiety, low mood, and lower life satisfaction. On the other hand, learning to approach stress with a more balanced and adaptive mindset can help support emotional resilience.</p><p>A great advantage is that these skills can be learned and cultivated. Just like riding a bike, emotional regulation skills improve with practice. Techniques such as noticing thoughts without reacting to them, shifting how we view stressful situations, and practicing kindness towards oneself can help people respond more adaptively to challenges.</p><p>Post-secondary education can be an especially demanding time. Many students experience academic, social, financial, and personal pressures all at once. Students often report high levels of stress, and many may not have had the opportunity to develop tools to manage it effectively. Brief, digital evidence-based exercises offer one possible way to support students. These interventions are short, flexible, and easy to access, making them well suited for busy academic schedules. However, even when effective tools are available, people do not always continue using them consistently.</p><p>Two strategies have been proposed to improve engagement. First, people may benefit from having a choice about which type of exercise they practice. Second, providing feedback about which exercises seem to work best for them may increase motivation and continued use. This study explores whether offering choice and personalized feedback improves engagement and subjective stress over time.</p><p>The current study aimed to create a web-based intervention platform for post-secondary students at a large Canadian university. The current study looked to answer three main questions:</p><ol><li><em>Do brief daily interventions help reduce students’ subjective stress?</em> During the first 12 days, participants practiced three short interventions designed to strengthen different emotional skills: not reacting automatically to difficult thoughts and emotions (non-reactivity); looking at stressful situations from a different perspective (reappraisal); and practicing kindness toward oneself (self-compassion) </li><li><em>Does having a choice of which intervention to continue to practice improve subjective stress? </em>Following the first 12-day exposure to three different interventions, some participants were randomly offered an option to choose which intervention they wanted to continue practicing for the next 12 days. Others were assigned to a less preferred condition. </li><li><em>Does personalized feedback improve subjective stress even further?</em> Some participants were not only given a choice but also received personalized feedback about which exercise appeared to help them the most during the first 12 days. </li></ol><p>We hypothesized that participants would experience lower subjective stress after the first 12 days of daily exercises. We also hypothesized that students who were allowed to choose their preferred exercise would experience greater improvements in subjective stress compared to those assigned to less preferred intervention. Lastly, participants who received both choice and personalized feedback would experience the greatest improvements in subjective stress and engagement. </p><p>We recognize that the intervention you were assigned to (non-reactivity, reappraisal, self-compassion) may not have been the one you would have chosen yourself. If you are interested in trying one of the other interventions, you are welcome to contact the investigator using the contact information below. We would be happy to provide access to the intervention of your choice. Please note that any data generated from this additional intervention would not be included in the research study, but you are welcome to experience the intervention for your own personal interest.</p><p>Please note that you will receive 3 hours of course research participation credit for participating in the study. If you have any further questions about the study, please contact the researcher at <a href="mailto:norman.farb@utoronto.ca">norman.farb@utoronto.ca</a> or (905) 828-3959. Additionally, if you have any questions about your rights as a participant, you can contact the Office of Research Ethics at ethics.review@utoronto.ca or call (416) 946-3273.</p><p>Once again, thank you for your participation in the study. We wish you the best.</p><p>Sincerely,</p><p>Prof. Norman Farb</p><p>Principal Investigator</p><p>Additional information can be found in:</p><p>Fiodorova, A., &amp; Farb, N. (2022). Brief daily self-care reflection for undergraduate well-being: a randomized control trial of an online intervention. Anxiety, Stress, &amp; Coping, 35(2), 158-170.</p><p>Wang, Y., &amp; Farb, N. A. S. (2025). An Exploratory Study of Chatbot-Based Mindfulness for Mental Health Support. <em>Mindfulness</em>, 1-20.</p>$debrief$)
  RETURNING id
)
UPDATE studies
SET active_debrief_form_id = ins.id
FROM ins
WHERE studies.id = 'dddddddd-0000-4000-8000-000000000001';
